_[All links forward to French text unless otherwise stated]_

Lightening the skin is a common practice in Africa where the sale of skin
lightening products is legal in many countries. However, the use of these
creams is not safe: stretch marks, pimples, hair, hypertension and diabetes
are all risks user take.

In Senegal, a whitening product named “Khess Petch” is creating controversy on
the web.

[Kiné Fatim Diop](http://observers.france24.com/profile/228512 "Voir le profil
utilisateur.") explains in ‘[A whiter skin in 15
days](http://observers.france24.com/fr/content/20120913-senegal-dakar-peau-
blanche-scandale-polemique-publicite-creme)‘:

> “Toute blanche”, c’est la traduction de l’expression en
> [Wolof](http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolof_\(langue\))« Khess Petch », du
> nom d’une toute nouvelle crème aux vertus prétendument éclaircissantes.

> “Completely white”, is how one translates the
> [Wolof](http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolof_\(langue\)) expression “Khess
> Petch”, the name of a new cream supposedly with skin whitening qualities.

Amadou Bakhaw DIAW on the site [Ndarinfo](http://www.ndarinfo.com/), writes in
‘[The “Khess Petch” campaign, an insult to our
identity](http://www.ndarinfo.com/La-publicite-Khess-Petch-une-insulte-a-
notre-identite_a3804.html)‘:

> Depuis une vingtaine de jours environ, un nouveau produit le « Khess Petch »
> a fait son apparition dans l’agglomération dakaroise, sur plus de 100
> panneaux publicitaires de 12 m2.

> Twenty days ago, a new product called “Khess Petch” appeared in the Dakar
> greater area, on more than 100 billboards of 12 square meters each.

With her blog post, ‘[A very clear skin at any cost: Understanding the
phenomena in Africa](http://www.nextafrique.com/showroom/styles-de-
vie/2127-une-peau-tres-claire-a-tout-prix-comprendre-le-phenomene-en-
afrique)‘, Carole Ouédraogo on the website
[NextAfrique](http://www.nextafrique.com/) explains that this phenomenon is
common in many African countries:

> Les [chercheurs estiment](http://gas.sagepub.com/content/22/3/281.short) que
> 25 % des femmes à Bamako au Mali utilisent des produits éclaircissants … en
> Afrique du Sud 35 % … au Sénégal 52 % …

> The [researchers estimate that roughly
> ](http://gas.sagepub.com/content/22/3/281.short) 25 % of women in Bamako,
> Mali use the skin lightening products… in South Africa 35% … in Senegal 52%
> …

And she adds:

> Les [femmes au Sénégal associent la peau
> claire](http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11982639) avec la beauté,
> l’élégance et un statut social élevé. Une [étude menée en
> Tanzanie](http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/%28ISSN%291471-6402;jsessionid=764A72B5DFBE3B41E4B5FEBCEC3888A2.d04t04)
> a révélé que nombre de Tanzaniens ont embrassé les idéaux de beautés
> eurocentriques.

> [Women in Senegal associate light
> skin](http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11982639) with beauty, elegance and
> high social status. One [study in Tanzania
> ](http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/%28ISSN%291471-6402;jsessionid=764A72B5DFBE3B41E4B5FEBCEC3888A2.d04t04)has
> revealed that many Tanzanians have also embraced Eurocentric ideals of
> beauty.

This video [in French] outlines the risks of skin lightening, uploaded to
YouTube by [myskreen](http://www.youtube.com/user/myskreen?feature=watch):

__<http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ADrWc2I0xzA>

On the blog A Toubab [[the word “toubab” means a westerner in West
Africa](http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toubab)] in Dakar, a blog post entitled
‘[The Xessalisation a.k.a the stupid quest for
whiteness](http://unetoubabadakar.wordpress.com/2012/09/14/la-xessalisation-
ou-la-stupide-quete-de-la-blancheur/)‘ tries to answer the question “Why
whiten your skin?” _:_

> _  
> _ Certaines pensent que les Sénégalais aiment la chair claire, elles se
> dépigmentent alors pour leur plaire . D’autres parlent de “complexes” …

> Some believe that Senegalese man love clear skin, so somewomen whiten their
> skin to please them. Other talk of an”inferiority complex” …

Blogger Fatou on Blackbeautybag goes further in his post ‘[Skin Whitening:
Practices, Challenges and
Accoutability](http://www.blackbeautybag.com/2012/09/le-blanchiment-de-la-
peau-les-pratiques.html?spref=tw)‘:

> Il y a les séquelles de l'esclavage et la colonisation. D'un point de vue
> psychologique, ce passé a laissé des séquelles chez beaucoup de personnes.
> Ce sentiment d'infériorité n'a pas totalement été éradiqué malheureusement
> [..] Il y'a des filles qui ne sont pas complexées à la base, mais à force de
> railleries venant de leurs proches, elles sautent le pas. Les remarques
> comme: TU ES NOIRE COMME LA NUIT, SI TU ES TROP NOIRE AUCUN HOMME NE VOUDRA
> DE TOI, et j'en passe des meilleures …

> These issues are related to sequels from slavery and colonialism. From a
> psychological point of view, the past has left its mark on many people. The
> complex of inferiority has not been totally eradicated unfortunately […]
> There are girls who aren't feeling inferior to start with, but by dint of
> taunts coming from the family they take the leap. Remarks like: YOU ARE
> BLACK AS THE NIGHT, IF YOU ARE TOO BLACK, NO MAN WILL WANT YOU, and the list
> goes on and on…

On the feeling of inferiority, blogger Mama Sarate writes a post to generate
controversy: ‘[From Black to White ↗ RACIAL
ASCENSION](http://www.mamasarate.com/archives/92)‘.

What can bloggers do to raise this issue and counter the trend ? Historically
in Senegal, a [decree has prohibited](http://www.afrik.com/article14408.html)
skin de-pigmentation among students in elementary, primary and secondary
school since 1979. In Jamaica, the question is also [identified as a public
health issue](http://www.stabroeknews.com/2010/archives/12/29/jamaica-to-step-
up-campaign-against-skin-bleaching/). In the United States last year, the
documentary [Dark
Girls](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UW31Te1awVw&feature=player_embedded#!)
(see preview below) illustrated and debated prejudices against women with dark
skin. In Kenya the top model[ Ajuma
Nasenyana](http://www.stabroeknews.com/2010/archives/12/29/jamaica-to-step-up-
campaign-against-skin-bleaching/) launched a campaign against skin whitening
products.

One of the [first counters
](http://observers.france24.com/fr/content/20120913-senegal-dakar-peau-
blanche-scandale-polemique-publicite-creme)from the blogger community is
explained by [Kiné Fatim Diop](http://observers.france24.com/profile/228512
"Voir le profil utilisateur."):

> Très rapidement, une mobilisation citoyenne dénonçant les risques de cette
> lotion [Khess Petch] est née sur les réseaux sociaux. Lancée sur Internet le
> 8 septembre, une pétition en ligne appelant le ministère de la Santé à
> mettre fin à cette campagne publicitaire a
> [recueilli](http://www.change.org/petitions/minist%C3%A8re-de-la-
> sant%C3%A9-et-de-l-action-sociale-mettre-fin-%C3%A0-la-campagne-
> publicitaire-khess-petch-toute-
> blanche?utm_campaign=share_button_modal&utm_medium=facebook&utm_source=share_petition&utm_term=28520207.)
> plus de 1.000 signatures en quatre jours.

> Rapidly, a citizen awareness project exposing the risks of the cream [Khess
> Petch] grew on social networks. Launched online on the 8 September, a
> petition calling for the Ministry of Health to put a halt to the advertising
> campaign, gathered more than 1,000 signatures in four days.

[@K_Sociial](https://twitter.com/K_Sociial) on Twitter mused:

> [@K_Sociaal](https://twitter.com/K_Sociial/status/245977528743915520): Je
> vais bientôt créer : “Nioul kouk” [toute noire] vous allez voir. Les filles
> deviendront bleues ! …

> [@K_Sociaal](https://twitter.com/K_Sociial/status/245977528743915520): I
> will soon create : “Nioul kouk” [all black] you will see. The girls will
> become blue! …

Bloggers and infographics designers took the idea to task and organized a
counter-campaign: “We see your Khess Petch (completely white) campaign and we
raise its **** counter: [Nioul Kouk](http://www.sengeek.com/les-infographes-
senegalais-apportent-la-reponse-a-la-pub-khess-petch/) (completely black in
wolof)”.

